replies.text:
@JETZcorp Pretty presumptuous statement. I didn't need others to form an opinion on Avatar. I saw it in the cinemas, along with millions of others ... and immediately forgot about it! 
Avatar was literally built around its CGI and 3D gimmick. Once the fancy gimmicks wore thin, then you're left with a forgettable hollow & generic shell of a movie. The fact that these movies are forgettable and completely culturally irrelevant probably stems from how cliche it all is when you strip away all the said fancy gimmicks. 
You are really fighting against the tsunami here!

@NotChris03
Imperial Guard wouldn’t lose a step marching through and reclaiming Pandora 
Heck, this place can be considered a vacation planet compared to the horrors of the galaxy and warp the men facing daily

@TheElmozusFlame Yes, i was expecting more desert, arid biomes naturally formed on the planet for whatever reason, Red-skinned and/or sand-skinned and are known for their violence or maybe they expose the hypocrisy of the blue Navi (They massacred some of the other ones), humanity begins building a big army, which actually has consequences and even Eywa is unable to stop humanities wrath, the last shot showing a large ship appearing in high-orbit, metallic, looks like a war vessel but 'primitive', showing a name on the side, showing that mankind has stopped pissing around now and is going full in. Also showing how Eywa is actually quite sadistic at times as well. Tensions between the family, showing more why humanity needs another place to stay. And more practical effects as well. And less wooden characters. 

And not deleting a new tribe as soon as it happens. Could even make Jake do some questionable things to help his family. Something tangible. Maybe even showcasing a small human settlement getting wiped out brutality. 

Just something of substance at the very least. Shame really.

@SammaclauseGamgee Yeah, I was wondering if they were planning on a colour-coded direction, or if literally every being on this planet is just a different type of blue. Then again, the first Avatar was kind of just the nature/green ones, and yet they were blue. Of course, if blue = green, then the fire ones should have actually been purple or yellow, I guess. The second ones actually were water/blue ones, and they were just a different blue. 

I know it's a minor point, but I think the entire skin colour issues shows us just how stupid the entire post-Avatar 1 idea really is -- nobody asked for it, nobody even saw it coming to begin with, and it's not needed at all. Now he claims that he started working on 2, 3, and 4 back in 2010 and always planned on making many of them? And he claimed that he wrote Avatar 1 back in 1995 but didn't have the tech to make it happen, so was just building up his other films and testing the tech until it was possible. 

I have to say... Avatar 2 really does seem like Titanic II: I Was Drunk When I Wrote This One. I refuse to watch 3-4 after 2. I'm actually a fan of the first one, though, other than the very clear anti-Western narratives, and very basic archetypes, but it's good fun, and at least reasonable, and doesn't utterly insult your time as a viewer!

@Ryuji777x The movie is fun.
It was better than the second one and, from what it seems, has more content than the first.
As for the characters, the fire people should have had more screen time; there was too much water for a fire movie. The witch has more charisma than the protagonist's wife and had great chemistry with Colonel Miles.

@p5ych0p4th Star wars didnt have no content in between movies tho? They had many books what is now known as the legends era. They did also have a few tv shows and video games (sure they probably werent good but still its something). With all of this stuff between those SIXTEEN years, its not easy to forget those movies. 

Also with the prequels, in between the movies we did get games based on the movies as well as many other games such as podracing, Knights of the Old Republic and the battlefront games. 

After the prequels we had 3 lego games (4 if you count the complete saga), many other video games focusing on new characters and the tv series the Clone Wars before disney bought the franchise. So no both franchises are not on the same level.

@rafresendenrafresenden.1644 Evil for who?
Not for the humans. Which we are.
The only thing that gives negative context to what the humans are doing is when a human becomes blue, then suddenly what the humans are doing is bad because the blue human decided so.
